Lab Seven: Recurrent Network Architectures¶

By Xiangying Chang, Fang Qi, Rui Lin, Shimeng Yuan¶

Business Understanding¶

This dataset consists of a few million Amazon customer reviews (input text) and star ratings (output labels) for learning how to train fastText for sentiment analysis. In this case, the classes are label1 and label2. Label 1 means 1 and 2 star reviews and label 2 means 4 and 5 star reviews.

Nowadays, shopping online is a common way in the United States. And the competition in the this area is very fierce. The United States is one of the largest online markets around the world. In the overall US online market, Amazon is an important component. People are always motivated by the cheaper price, free shipping and convenience to shop on Amazon. And the real-time updated reviews is one of the most important way to help the online business to develop better by learning form the market through the reviews.

In this lab, we used Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) architectures to do the prediction task. Through the Recurrent Neural Network architectures and sentiment analysis of the reviews on Amazon, we are able to help buyers and sellers to identify the most significant words leading to the star of the reviews. From the prediction result, the sellers could have an idea what kind of reviews are beneficial to their products. The buyers could filter the reviews to choose the most suitable goods.

Finally, it could also be generalized by other similar companies to predict the results to better improve their goods and services, like Alibaba, Groupon and so on.

Dataset Source: https://www.kaggle.com/bittlingmayer/amazonreviews

1. Preparation¶

1.1 Data Preparation¶

Our task is to predict the labels among different reviews. Due to the large dataset, we first chose the first 10000 datasets and removed all the punctuations digits and stopwords. And then we converted words to indexes using tokenizer. Here we used tokenizer.fit_on_texts as our method. Finally we split our data in stratified k-fold method.

doclist = []
def getdoclist(docs,splitStr='__label__'):
    for i in range(len(docs)):
        line = str(lines[i])
        splitText = line.split(splitStr)
        secHalf = splitText[1]
        text = secHalf[2:len(secHalf)-1].lower()
        text = re.sub('\d','0', text)
        sentiment = secHalf[0]
        doclist.append([text,sentiment])
    return doclist

1.2 Evaluation Metrics¶

There are four common evaluation metrics: Accuracy, Precision, Recall, F1-score. In order to choose the appropriate metric, we need to compare these different metrics based on our data. For each word in the reviews, there are 4 cases:

  1. True Positive - Prediction is label1 and class is also label1.
  2. False Positive - Prediction is label1 but class is label2.
  3. False Negative - Prediction is label2 but class is label1.
  4. True Negative - Prediction is label2 and class is also label2. The reason why we mention these four conditions is they are related to four common evaluation metrics. Accuracy indicates how many proportions of our sample are correct, this includes both TP and TN, however we want to focus on TP because it is what we would like to use in practical applications. We hope people can recognize words from the reviews and get the right prediction result.

Next, considering Precision, Recall and F1-score together. Precision reflects the ability to identify type I error, Recall reflects the ability to identify type II error, they both focus on TP. F1-score is the combination of these two metrics and it finds a balance between Precision and Recall, so F1 score is better.

And for our business circumstances, we need to help people combine the reviews and stars together, because most people can't combine different reviews with corresponding stars, so we need to improve the accuracy, F1-score is also good to solve this problem. Therefore, we decide to select F1-score as our metric.

F1 scores has macro average and micro average methods.A macro-average will compute the metric independently for each class and then take the average (hence treating all classes equally), it counts the TP, FP, FN, and TN of each class, calculate their respective precisions and recalls, get the respective F1 values, and then take the average to get the macro-F1. Micro-average will aggregate the contributions of all classes to compute the average metric. In our case, it is equally distributed in two classes, so we chose the macro-average method.

1.3 Data Splitting¶

We are considering Stratified K-fold and stratified Shuffle splits as cross validation methods for our model. They both split the data into n_splits parts. However, there are some differences between them. For Stratified K-fold, the dataset is simply divided into k folds, and training proportion in each iteration is k-1/k. For stratified Shuffle splits, it randomly shuffles the dataset each time before splitting and splits n_splits time, so test sets may be overlapped, and it is also possible that some data would never appear in the train set or test set.

In our dataset, we want to predict the star level based on each word in the reviews. Since in stratified Shuffle splits, the same samples could be selected many times in test data, so it will result in some words never showed in test data. This makes the result become less convinced and less accurate. So we would like to use Stratified K-fold as our cross validation method.

2. Modeling¶

We select f1_score as the evaluation metric, since Precision, Recall and F1 metrics have been removed from metrics.py, so we try to calculate f1_score by using code. The code we used in the following cell are all from reference https://stackoverflow.com/questions/43547402/how-to-calculate-f1-macro-in-keras¶

In [65]:
# The code we used in the following cell are all from reference https://stackoverflow.com/questions/43547402/how-to-calculate-f1-macro-in-keras
from keras import backend as K

def f1_score(y_true, y_pred):
    def recall(y_true, y_pred):
        true_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true * y_pred, 0, 1)))
        possible_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true, 0, 1)))
        recall = true_positives / (possible_positives + K.epsilon())
        return recall

    def precision(y_true, y_pred):
        true_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true * y_pred, 0, 1)))
        predicted_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_pred, 0, 1)))
        precision = true_positives / (predicted_positives + K.epsilon())
        return precision
    precision = precision(y_true, y_pred)
    recall = recall(y_true, y_pred)
    return 2*((precision*recall)/(precision+recall+K.epsilon()))

from keras.models import Sequential, Input, Model
from keras.layers import Dense
from keras.layers import LSTM, GRU
from keras.layers.embeddings import Embedding

top_words = 10000
max_review_length = 50
NUM_CLASSES = 1
EMBED_SIZE = 50
i = 0
score1 = []
val_score1 = []

for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X,y):
    i = i + 1
    print('Fold:', i)
    X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    print(X_train.shape, y_train.shape)
    input_holder = Input(shape=(X_train.shape[1], ))
    shared_embed = Embedding(top_words, # input dimension (max int of OHE)
                             EMBED_SIZE, # output dimension size
                             input_length=max_review_length)(input_holder) 

    x = LSTM(50, dropout=0.2, recurrent_dropout=0.2)(shared_embed)
    x = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='sigmoid')(x)
    lstm_rnn=Model(inputs=input_holder,outputs=x)
    lstm_rnn.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                     optimizer='rmsprop', 
                     metrics=[f1score])
    history1 = lstm_rnn.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=10, batch_size=64, validation_data=(X_test, y_test))
    score = np.sum(history1.history['f1score'])/10
    val_score = np.sum(history1.history['val_f1score'])/10
    score1.append(score)
    val_score1.append(val_score)
    
print(lstm_rnn.summary())

import keras

NUM_TOP_WORDS = None
MAX_ART_LEN = 50 # maximum and minimum number of words

word_index = tokenizer.word_index
NUM_TOP_WORDS = len(word_index) if NUM_TOP_WORDS==None else NUM_TOP_WORDS
top_words = min((len(word_index),NUM_TOP_WORDS))
print('Found %s unique tokens. Distilled to %d top words.' % (len(word_index),top_words))

X = sequence.pad_sequences(tokenized_train, maxlen=MAX_ART_LEN)

%%time
EMBED_SIZE = 100
# the embed size should match the file you load glove from
embeddings_index = {}
f = open('../input/glove6b100dtxt/glove.6B.100d.txt')
# save key/array pairs of the embeddings
#  the key of the dictionary is the word, the array is the embedding
for line in f:
    values = line.split()
    word = values[0]
    coefs = np.asarray(values[1:], dtype='float32')
    embeddings_index[word] = coefs
f.close()

print('Found %s word vectors.' % len(embeddings_index))

# now fill in the matrix, using the ordering from the
#  keras word tokenizer from before
embedding_matrix = np.zeros((len(word_index) + 1, EMBED_SIZE))
for word, i in word_index.items():
    embedding_vector = embeddings_index.get(word)
    if embedding_vector is not None:
        # words not found in embedding index will be all-zeros.
        embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector

print(embedding_matrix.shape)

top_words = 20000
max_review_length = 50
NUM_CLASSES = 1
EMBED_SIZE = 50

score3 = []
val_score3 = []

for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X,y):
    i = i + 1
    print('Fold:', i)
    X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    print(X_train.shape, y_train.shape)
    input_holder = Input(shape=(X_train.shape[1], ))
    shared_embed = Embedding(top_words, # input dimension (max int of OHE)
                             EMBED_SIZE, # output dimension size
                             input_length=max_review_length)(input_holder) 

    x = GRU(50, dropout=0.2, recurrent_dropout=0.2)(shared_embed)
    x = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='sigmoid')(x)
    gru_rnn=Model(inputs=input_holder,outputs=x)
    gru_rnn.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                    optimizer='rmsprop', 
                    metrics=[f1score])
    history3 = gru_rnn.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=10, batch_size=64, validation_data=(X_test, y_test))
    score = np.sum(history3.history['f1score'])/10
    val_score = np.sum(history3.history['val_f1score'])/10
    score3.append(score)
    val_score3.append(val_score)
    
print(gru_rnn.summary())

NUM_CLASSES = 2

    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    y_train_ohe = keras.utils.to_categorical(y_train) 
    y_test_ohe = keras.utils.to_categorical(y_test)
    
    gru_glove = Sequential()
    gru_glove.add(embedding_layer)
    gru_glove.add(GRU(100, dropout=0.2, recurrent_dropout=0.2))
    gru_glove.add(Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='sigmoid'))

2.2 Adjust hyper-parameters¶

To improve generalization performance, we changed the follow parameters for the all 4 models:

  • change EMBED_SIZE from 50 to 100
  • change dropout from 0.2 to 0.1
  • change batch_size from 64 to 128

Adjusted LSTM (Trained From Scratch)¶

In [78]:
top_words = 10000
max_review_length = 50
NUM_CLASSES = 1
EMBED_SIZE = 100
i = 0
score5 = []
val_score5 = []

for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X,y):
    i = i + 1
    print('Fold:', i)
    X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    print(X_train.shape, y_train.shape)
    input_holder = Input(shape=(X_train.shape[1], ))
    shared_embed = Embedding(top_words, # input dimension (max int of OHE)
                             EMBED_SIZE, # output dimension size
                             input_length=max_review_length)(input_holder) 

    x = LSTM(50, dropout=0.1, recurrent_dropout=0.1)(shared_embed)
    x = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='sigmoid')(x)
    lstm_rnn_2=Model(inputs=input_holder,outputs=x)
    lstm_rnn_2.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                       optimizer='rmsprop', 
                       metrics=[f1score])
    history5 = lstm_rnn_2.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=10, batch_size=128, validation_data=(X_test, y_test))
    score = np.sum(history5.history['f1score'])/10
    val_score = np.sum(history5.history['val_f1score'])/10
    score5.append(score)
    val_score5.append(val_score)
    
print(lstm_rnn_2.summary())

top_words = 20000
max_review_length = 50
NUM_CLASSES = 1
EMBED_SIZE = 100
i = 0
score7 = []
val_score7 = []

for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X,y):
    i = i + 1
    print('Fold:', i)
    X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    print(X_train.shape, y_train.shape)
    input_holder = Input(shape=(X_train.shape[1], ))
    shared_embed = Embedding(top_words, # input dimension (max int of OHE)
                             EMBED_SIZE, # output dimension size
                             input_length=max_review_length)(input_holder) 

    x = GRU(50, dropout=0.1, recurrent_dropout=0.1)(shared_embed)
    x = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='sigmoid')(x)
    gru_rnn_2=Model(inputs=input_holder,outputs=x)
    gru_rnn_2.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                    optimizer='rmsprop', 
                    metrics=[f1score])
    history7 = gru_rnn_2.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=10, batch_size=128, validation_data=(X_test, y_test))
    score = np.sum(history7.history['f1score'])/10
    val_score = np.sum(history7.history['val_f1score'])/10
    score7.append(score)
    val_score7.append(val_score)
    
print(gru_rnn_2.summary())

2.3 Using the best RNN, add a second recurrent chain¶

top_words = 10000
max_review_length = 50
NUM_CLASSES = 1
EMBED_SIZE = 100
i = 0
score9 = []
val_score9 = []

for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X,y):
    i = i + 1
    print('Fold:', i)
    X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]
    print(X_train.shape, y_train.shape)
    input_holder = Input(shape=(X_train.shape[1], ))
    shared_embed = Embedding(top_words, # input dimension (max int of OHE)
                             EMBED_SIZE, # output dimension size
                             input_length=max_review_length)(input_holder) 

    x = LSTM(50, dropout=0.1, recurrent_dropout=0.1,return_sequences=True)(shared_embed)
    x = LSTM(50, dropout=0.1, recurrent_dropout=0.1)(x)
    x = Dense(NUM_CLASSES, activation='sigmoid')(x)
    lstm_rnn_3=Model(inputs=input_holder,outputs=x)
    lstm_rnn_3.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                     optimizer='rmsprop', 
                     metrics=[f1score])
    history9 = lstm_rnn_3.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=10, batch_size=128, validation_data=(X_test, y_test))
    score = np.sum(history9.history['f1score'])/10
    val_score = np.sum(history9.history['val_f1score'])/10
    score9.append(score)
    val_score9.append(val_score)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.subplot(2,2,1)
    plt.plot(history9.history['f1score'])

    plt.ylabel('F1_score %')
    plt.title('Training')
    plt.subplot(2,2,2)
    plt.plot(history9.history['val_f1score'])
    plt.title('Validation')

    plt.subplot(2,2,3)
    plt.plot(history9.history['loss'])
    plt.ylabel('MSE Training Loss')
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

    plt.subplot(2,2,4)
    plt.plot(history9.history['val_loss'])
    plt.xlabel('epochs')
    
print(lstm_rnn_3.summary())

2.4 Compare the Performance¶

In order to compare the performance of all 9 models, we decided to use histogram plot and Receiver operating characteristics and area under the curve (ROC & AUC) to do the comperation to determine which method is superior.

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc
from scipy import interp
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

def plot_roc(model,model_name):
    cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)
    kfold = cv.split(X,y)

    mean_tpr = 0.0
    mean_fpr = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)
    all_tpr = []

    for i, (train, test) in enumerate(kfold):
        probas = model.predict(X[test])

        perclass_mean_tpr = 0.0
        roc_auc = 0
        classes = np.unique(y[train])
    # get the mean fpr and tpr, per class
        for j in classes:
            fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y[test],
                                         probas)
            perclass_mean_tpr += interp(mean_fpr, fpr, tpr)
            perclass_mean_tpr[0] = 0.0
            roc_auc += auc(fpr, tpr)
        
        perclass_mean_tpr /= len(classes)
        roc_auc /= len(classes)
        mean_tpr += perclass_mean_tpr
        plt.plot(mean_fpr,perclass_mean_tpr,'--',lw=1,label='Mean Class ROC fold %d (area = %0.5f)'
                   % (i+1, roc_auc))
    
    mean_tpr /= 5
    mean_auc = auc(mean_fpr, mean_tpr)
    plt.plot(mean_fpr,perclass_mean_tpr,'k-',lw=2,label='Total Mean ROC (area = %0.5f)'
                   % (mean_auc))
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.xlabel('false positive rate')
    plt.ylabel('true positive rate')
    plt.title('%s ROC Curve'%(model_name))
    plt.grid()
    

def plot_roc_2(model,model_name):
    cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)
    kfold = cv.split(X,y)

    mean_tpr = 0.0
    mean_fpr = np.linspace(0, 1, 100)
    all_tpr = []

    for i, (train, test) in enumerate(kfold):
        probas = model.predict(X[test])

        perclass_mean_tpr = 0.0
        roc_auc = 0
        classes = np.unique(y[train])
    # get the mean fpr and tpr, per class
        for j in classes:
            fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y[test],
                                         probas[:, j],
                                         pos_label=j)
            perclass_mean_tpr += interp(mean_fpr, fpr, tpr)
            perclass_mean_tpr[0] = 0.0
            roc_auc += auc(fpr, tpr)
        
        perclass_mean_tpr /= len(classes)
        roc_auc /= len(classes)
        mean_tpr += perclass_mean_tpr
        plt.plot(mean_fpr,perclass_mean_tpr,'--',lw=1,label='Mean Class ROC fold %d (area = %0.5f)'
                   % (i+1,roc_auc))
    
    mean_tpr /= 5
    mean_auc = auc(mean_fpr, mean_tpr)
    plt.plot(mean_fpr,perclass_mean_tpr,'k-',lw=2,label='Total Mean ROC (area = %0.5f)'
                   % (mean_auc))
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.xlabel('false positive rate')
    plt.ylabel('true positive rate')
    plt.title('%s ROC Curve'%(model_name))
    plt.grid()

def compare_rnn(lstm_rnn, lstm_glove, gru_rnn, gru_glove,lstm_rnn_2, lstm_glove_2, gru_rnn_2, gru_glove_2, lstm_rnn_3):
